Mystery solved: That's why we can't tickle ourselves
A kind of brake in the cerebrum prevents people from tickling themselves, scientists at Humboldt University in Berlin found out on Thursday night, using experiments on rats, and they also made progress on the question of why children fight tickling so hard, only to ask for more.
Finally, it has also been shown why the mere approach of a tickling hand triggers laughter even before the touch. This is due to a deep-seated layer in the cerebellum, which triggers laughter already in the expectation of the tickle.
The data showed that previous research showed that rats react with "laughter" in the ultrasonic range when tickled by humans.This "laughter" is conveyed by the part of the cerebral cortex that is central to the processing of haptic perception.
Laughter is suppressed during self-touching
The researchers had previously assumed that the brain could distinguish between self-touch and touch by others - hence why people cannot tickle themselves. But the Berlin researchers now found in experiments on rats that laughter as well as the activity of the corresponding area of the cerebral cortex during self-touch is suppressed. This is also true when living creatures clean themselves. During the stranger's touch and tickling, the activity in the brain and the impulse to laugh were intensified by the scientists.
But if self-touch and other people's touches occur at the same time, laughter is suppressed, too, suggesting that the rat brain cannot distinguish between self-touch and other people's touches, and the new findings suggest that humans cannot self-tickle because self-touch activates a brake in the cerebellum.
The rats were also trained to tickle themselves, and sometimes failed to do so in the experiment, sometimes showing flight or fear, and the ambivalence was similar to that of children.
