Study on the causes of heart disease
Smoking, obesity, unhealthy diet - there are risk factors for cardiovascular disease, but what really triggers heart failure or a heart attack?
By analysing the genetic material of 9 000 people, scientists in Hamburg and Switzerland are seeking to discover the causes of cardiovascular disease in greater detail.
The research project is the largest of its kind in the German-speaking area, the University Hospital Hamburg-Eppendorf (UKE) announced on Friday.
The study, which was conducted by the University of California, Berkeley, in collaboration with the National Institute of Health, found that the risk of heart disease is increased by the combination of obesity, smoking, and unhealthy eating habits.
Currently, more than 4,000 of the some 20,000 relevant human genes have known potential disease-causing changes in their DNA - so-called mutations - and some 200 are being added each year, the clinic said.
The aim of the five-year project is to develop new options for the prevention, detection and treatment of cardiac arrhythmias, heart failure and heart attacks, among others.The data could also be used to research other common diseases, says Stefan Blankenberg, head of the University's cardiovascular centre.New insights into the interaction between heart and brain, heart and kidney and cancer are possible.
The chairman of the Kühne Foundation, Klaus-Michael Kühne (82), also stressed that there is a strong will to use the data also for research into other diseases. The foundation's clinic in Davos has so far mainly dealt with allergies. Now a Center for Cardiovascular Precision Medicine should be created on the medical campus there and a professorship for bioinformatics should be created.
The healthy participants' bioprobes are from Hamburgers who are also taking part in the "Hamburg City Health Study". With 45,000 subjects, the clinic says, this is the largest local health study in the world.
