Caution: NEVER charge your smartphone without a cable
Practical but Harmful
Inductive technology via Qi standard is extremely practical, but should not be used.
Since several new smartphones have recently come on the market, which support wireless charging and are selling very well - especially the new iPhone 11 models, we would like to recall a study from the beginning of July.
Higher temperature is killing the battery.
Researchers warn against wireless charging of smartphones. This is extremely harmful to the devices according to the findings of the Univerity of Warwick. The reason for this is the significantly greater heat development. If you charge a mobile phone normally by cable, the battery heats up to 27 degrees within three hours. When charging wirelessly, the researchers have always measured over 30 degrees even with the perfect alignment of the smartphone on the charging pad. If the mobile phone is located next to the coil, the temperature rises even higher. In addition, the wattage of the charging pad also rises, which in turn drives up the power consumption.
Capacity and life
According to the researchers, the temperature is a decisive factor for the battery's durability. Every single degree plays a role. Charging at higher temperatures not only reduces the battery's capacity, but also reduces its overall durability. The battery life is therefore shorter. The researchers therefore recommend that the smartphone always be charged by cable. Since a battery replacement in modern smartphones is always associated with high costs, this may be a helpful tip. Apple has recently increased the cost of a battery replacement even once - for all iPhones.
Practical
The technology is extremely convenient: just place the device on a suitable charging pad - these are now installed in many restaurants, airports, hotels and cars - and the battery is charged without the hassle of cables and the hassle of plugging.As a global standard is being established with Qi (stands for inductive energy transfer), which, exceptionally, even Apple is involved in, there are hardly any limitations.However, the researchers say the technology should only be used in exceptional cases.
