Actor and Youtuber accuses Egypt's ruler of being a "spoiler": Mohamed Ali prefers to stay abroad for now.
The two men who have the power to make blood flow again on the streets of Egypt spent the past week both abroad. One of them swam back to Cairo airport on Friday. President Abdelfattah al-Sisi returned from the UN General Assembly. The former general who in 2013 deposed the Muslim Brotherhood's Mohammed Morsi, the country's first freely elected head of state, had spent a pleasant time in New York: US President Donald Trump had vowed to be careful with political Islam and lost no silver coins over human rights violations on the Nile - in a week in which Egyptian security forces arrested hundreds of people for not protesting against the president. "He said that the Egyptian airports had caused the Iranian refugees to fear the state of Egypt".
The 45-year-old actor was known only to a minority of Egyptians weeks ago, but now he is the voice that dominates the political discourse in the country's cafes, apartments and tea rooms: with his YouTube channel, "Mohamed Ali's Secrets", Ali is calling on his countrymen to rise up against Sisi.
He addresses the head of state directly and in a very rustic language. While the people are hungry, the president revels in luxury and builds magnificent new palaces, it says. The military leadership, on which Sisi bases his rule, Ali accuses of corruption and enrichment. Because he did business with these gentlemen for 15 years in his second career as a contractor, he seems to know quite exactly what he is talking about - at least that is the impression of many Egyptians, as the click counts that are about to explode show.
Last week, after thousands of people demonstrated against his rule for the first time since Sisi took power, and almost 2,000 citizens, including prominent civil society figures, human rights lawyers and opposition politicians, were arrested, Ali called for a "million march" on Friday. It was unlikely that so many people would actually take to the streets. But there were sporadic smaller protests, for example in Gisheh near Cairo and in China near Luxor. Videos on social media showed protests whose participants accused Al-Sisi of corruption and demanded his departure.
In the city of Mansura in the Nile Delta, where protesters tore apart banners bearing the portrait of the president last week, a massive police presence was reported on Friday. Security forces set up checkpoints in the city and on the exit roads. In Cairo, several metro stations were closed for "maintenance work" in the city center, most of the streets around Tahrir Square, the heart of the 2011 revolution, were blocked. And in Rabaa Square, where in 2013 supporters of the Muslim Brotherhood gathered in the mud, the army opened fire on them and killed up to 800 people, another measure was to prevent the unrest from spreading: the Zukunf Sisene party wanted to hold a large gathering for the president here.
Mohamed Ali's precautions prompted a change in his tactics: "Our target doesn't have to be Tahrir Square", Ali told his video camera in Barcelona. "Let's not clash with police officers". But this is not a retreat: "Egypt is Tahrir Square".
If the provider promises too much performance
If the Internet connection always seems to be much slower than advertised by the provider, there are several ways of checking.
The Commission has also adopted a proposal for a directive on the protection of the environment in the event of accidents at work, which is to be incorporated into the Treaty of Amsterdam.
Finally, the transfer rates promised in advance are part of the contract and should therefore be achieved, explains the Consumer Centre of Bavaria.
If the connection always seems much slower than advertised by the provider, there are several ways of checking the connection: the measuring tools of the Federal Network Agency (BNetzA) measure the actual data transmission rates and compare them with the rate agreed in the contract.
"However, the tests of the suppliers are carried out according to the specifications of the supplier and are therefore not uniformly and objectively calculated", the Consumer Centre of Bavaria points out.
If the connection is much slower than announced, customers can give the provider a reasonable period of time, usually 14 days, to deliver the promised service.
If the customer does not receive any compensation, even after several requests, he can cancel the contract and, in some cases, claim damages, but if he does not receive any compensation, he can only appeal.
