Green politician to answer for embarrassing photo incident
The leader of the Canadian Greens, Elizabeth May, in the election campaign - was the cup manipulated for this reason?
The Canadian Green leader is pictured holding a disposable cup in her hand, but now it's out that the cup has been tampered with.
The reusable coffee cup with metal straw was never held in the hand of Elizabeth May, the leader of the Canadian Greens. On the party's website, she was seen in a photo with this cup, talking to citizens. However, the photo had been published before and also circulated to the media - and the cup was still a schnoeder (papp) cup, as reported by the Canadian National Post.
Green Leader to answer for photo failure
The National Post accused May of manipulating the party and producing fake news to make the party more credible on environmental issues, amid a House of Commons election campaign that is also plaguing Trudeau over a bribery scandal.
The photo went viral on social media, fueling the discussion about fake news. One user shares a contrast of the photos and writes: "The Greens manipulate a photo of their chairman to hide their disposable cup".
May expressed her shock and insisted on her blog that she knew nothing about this action. To emphasize this, she posted the original: she, in conversation with citizens, a cup in her hand. However, the right one, she said, was made of bamboo. She always had it with her. A spokeswoman of the party said that it was only to cover the Parago part in the picture, and not to cover up something.
May writes that she feels sorry for the employee who did this. "I don't want to call him stupid, but there was nothing to hide", she tells the Guardian, and asks her over-committed team, "If they want to edit a picture again, can they do something with my face to make me look younger?"
The German Greens have also been hit by shitstorms over their use of single-use plastics or air travel - but their pictures were not photoshopped.
Influencerin wants free upgrade: Lifetime ban from Cathay
Jaqueline Ng had allegedly received a letter from Cathay Pacific promising her an upgrade, but when she asked for it at check-in, she was denied boarding - and she should never be allowed to fly with Cathay again.
To get a spontaneous upgrade to business class, which is the dream of many passengers, sometimes you get lucky and the staff at check-in offers you a free transfer from economy class.
But this case shows how not to do it: A self-proclaimed influencer actively asked Cathay Pacific for a free upgrade. Jaqueline Ng has over 65,000 followers on Instagram. She flew from Taiwan to New York on May 30 and back on June 7.
On the way in, Jaqueline was denied an upgrade by her staff, despite showing an email to her allegedly suggesting an upgrade by Cathay Pacific, which the influencer claims was sent to her by a marketing employee of the airline, who accused Jaqueline of forging the email.
On the return flight, Jacqueline tried again to get an upgrade for the long-haul flight, this time the woman allegedly showed the same email, but with a different reference number. The staff at JFK airport were skeptical: they checked with the central office. And in fact, the employee from whom the email allegedly came, allegedly cut off contact with Jacqueline by mail. This was also confirmed by the mail system, in which the messages did not appear.
Airline officials at the airport canceled Jaqueline's ticket and imposed a lifetime ban on her from Cathay Pacific, forcing her to buy a new ticket to Taiwan for $1,400.
The influencer turned to Elliot Advocacy, a consumer advocacy firm, for help with her case, because while Cathay had reimbursed her the price of her original ticket, Jaqueline was also claiming the cost of the new ticket.
But as long as Jaqueline doesn't submit the email metadata, the case is clear: Cathay believes the influencer committed fraud, she is banned from future flights, and the airline's terms of service state that she doesn't have to pay for the new flight.
Oil prices fall after report of ceasefire in Yemen
Oil prices fell by more than a dollar in the shortest time on Friday afternoon. The latest price was a barrel (159 liters) of the North Sea variety Brent at $61.83 - about 1.4 percent less than the previous day. The price of a barrel of the American variety West Texas Intermediate (WTI) fell by 1.3 percent to $55.77.
The move was triggered by a Wall Street Journal report on a ceasefire in Yemen, which Saudi Arabia is said to have agreed to in four areas.
A drone attack on Saudi Arabia's oil facilities in mid-September halted five percent of global oil production. Iran-aligned Houthi rebels in Yemen have claimed responsibility for the attacks. Saudi Arabia and the US government have blamed Iran. A ceasefire would ease political tensions in the region.
If a deal is reached, the focus could be on growth and demand, Ole Hansen, head of Saxo Bank's commodity strategy department, told Bloomberg.
The price of oil is continuing its downward trend of the past few days, with WTI oil costing almost 59 dollars a barrel a week ago, and Brent oil costing almost 65 dollars a barrel.
Bloomberg recently reported, citing insiders, that oil repair work in Saudi Arabia is progressing faster than expected after the mid-September attack, and that production has reached a volume of eight million barrels per day and is moving back toward the original volume.
Recently, there have been several press reports citing insiders reporting rapid progress by the state-owned oil company Saudi Aramco in repairs, but crude oil experts point out that Saudi Aramco is currently planning an IPO and wants to avoid negative headlines.
At the same time, there was some relief in the conflict between Iran and the West: The British oil tanker "Stena Impero" is on its way to leave the port more than two months after being detained by Iran and recently granted permission. The crew is now preparing for departure, while the ship remains at anchor, the ship's captain Erik Hånell told Swedish radio on Friday morning in an SMS.
However, the US has announced that it will deploy missiles and troops to Iran's arch-enemy Saudi Arabia, and fears of an escalation between the Islamic Republic and countries such as the US and the UK have driven oil prices up significantly in recent weeks.
