Russia's doping: further Russian manipulation proved
The Moscow analysis laboratory is being manipulated, according to David Howman, former director of the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) and now head of integrity at the World Athletics Federation.
As the World Athletics Championships kick off, new details emerge about the doping scandal in Russia - and they destroy the little credibility that Russian sports had gained at the beginning of the year, and only partially regained.In January 2019, the Moscow Doping Laboratory finally delivered the requested samples from 2012 to 2015 to the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA).Now it turned out: they were falsified.
In December 2014, systematic fraud in Russian sports was revealed. The WADA had banned the Russian Anti-Doping Agency (Rusada) for three years. During this time, Russian athletes were not completely banned from the world stage. The International Olympic Committee allowed around 270 athletes from the country to compete under a neutral flag at the 2016 Summer Games in Rio after an individual test, and 168 Russian athletes were at the start at the Winter Games in February 2018.
Positive findings are missing
The following September, WADA lifted the ban on Rusada, but demanded access to the lab and the samples it had collected, which would reveal the extent of the cover-up of doping cases in the state doping system and help punish athletes after the fact.
The chairman of the IAAF's Independent Integrity Commission (AIU) has now confirmed that the doping data from the Moscow analysis laboratory was manipulated. "Yes. We received the data nine months ago. We should check whether the task force received the correct data", said David Howman in an interview with the "Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung" on Friday. "We have found numerous discrepancies between the data received from a whistleblower and the data received from the Russen in January". Many positive findings were missing, which were mentioned in the McLaren report.
Not affected by the World Cup
This confirms the position of the IAAF: the athletics federation is the only organization that is sticking to the Russian ban. At the World Championships in Doha, 30 Russian athletes will start under a neutral flag. They had to prove that they train and undergo tests outside the Russian system.
Earlier this week, Wada revealed the manipulations and asked Russia to respond to the allegations within three weeks, and Russia now threatens to ban Rusada again, and in the worst case, to ban it from the 2020 Tokyo Olympics.
